data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Inventory

Your code has three APIs that throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8:

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Abort as control flow |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

### Key Paradigm Shift

.NET Framework: runtime **forcibly injects** `ThreadAbortException` mid-execution.
.NET 8: code must **voluntarily check** for cancellation. If you don't check, cancellation never happens.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);      // pass token for checkpoint
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in
                // the ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control whether to continue
                // via the loop condition. The loop will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully.
        // Join(timeout) replaces Sleep+Abort — it actually waits
        // for the thread rather than sleeping blindly.
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. There is NO equivalent to
            // Thread.Abort in .NET 8. See "Pitfalls" below.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical: You Must Fix `GetNextItem`

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the most important change — **if this call blocks forever, cancellation will never be observed** because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints.

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, cannot be cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until item available
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If you're using a raw `Monitor.Wait` or similar:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollIntervalMs);

// Replace ManualResetEvent.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { manualResetEvent, token.WaitHandle });
```

### Pitfalls Specific to This Code

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **`GetNextItem` still blocks** | If you don't pass the token into the blocking call, `Stop()` will wait forever. The old `Thread.Abort` would force-interrupt it; `.Cancel()` will not. |
| **`Thread.Join` timeout expires** | There is **no fallback** in .NET 8. You cannot force-kill a thread. If this is unacceptable, move uncooperative work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |
| **`volatile bool _running` removed** | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` replaces it. Don't keep both — it's redundant and confusing. |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Implement `IDisposable` on the host class. |
| **`catch (OperationCanceledException)` filter** | Always add `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations from inner calls with different tokens. |

### Validation Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` references remain
- ✅ No `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks remain  
- ✅ No `Thread.ResetAbort` calls remain
- ✅ `CancellationToken` passed through the full call chain
- ✅ Blocking call (`GetNextItem`) accepts and honors the token
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed
